# IAMouflage — Architecture

IAMouflage models **GCP attack techniques** (with their IAM preconditions) against a
**signature-detection corpus** as a **Neo4j** graph, and then finds — *by graph query alone,
with no ML model* — the attack scenarios the detections cannot catch. It is the knowledge
substrate (the manual **𝒦**) for the detection-priced planner: it establishes precisely
**what per-event signatures miss**, which is the gap the planner is meant to reason about.

---

## 1. The one idea: detections and techniques meet on operations

A detection catches a technique **only if the exact API operation the technique performs is
the same operation some rule is watching for in the audit log.** So detections and techniques
are **never joined by a direct edge**. They meet on a shared **`ApiMethod`** node — one GCP
operation, written in one canonical notation.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  T["Technique<br/>«I act here»"] -->|INVOKES| M["ApiMethod<br/>service.resource.verb"]
  R["DetectionRule<br/>«my rule watches here»"] -->|COVERS| M
  T -.->|"DETECTED_BY (derived) —<br/>only if COVERS + logged-by-default"| R
```

- A technique declares the IAM permissions it needs; a rule declares the audit `methodName`
  (or Workspace `eventName`) it matches. These are three incompatible notations, so **both
  sides are normalised** to one canonical operation signature `service.resource.verb`
  (`core/normalize.py`) — that string *is* the `ApiMethod` key.
- Normalisation is deliberately **conservative**: when unsure it emits a *different*
  signature, so ambiguous cases fail to match rather than matching falsely. Every blind-spot
  count is therefore a **lower bound**.
- The correlation surface is intentionally tiny — only a handful of `ApiMethod` nodes are both
  *invoked by a technique* and *covered by a rule*. **That smallness is the finding.**

---

## 2. When is a technique actually *detected*?

Matching an operation is not enough — the operation also has to be **written to a log that is
on by default**. GCP Cloud Audit Logs split into two tiers (`detection/logtype.py`):

| Log tier | What lands here | Default |
|---|---|---|
| **Admin Activity** | config / IAM / metadata **writes** | **always on** — a rule can see it |
| **Data Access** | reads, token minting, KMS decrypt, object/secret payloads | **off by default** — a rule never receives the event |

So every technique falls into exactly one bucket:

| `blind_class` | Meaning | Remedy |
|---|---|---|
| `DETECTED` | a matched operation is logged by default | — |
| `RULE_GAP` (A) | operation **is** logged, but **no rule** matches it | write a signature — the evidence is already in the logs |
| `TELEMETRY_GAP` (B) | operation is Data Access, **off by default** | *no signature can ever fire* until logging is reconfigured |

The load-bearing distinction: **`logged` ≠ `detected`.** A `DETECTED_BY` edge is derived only
when a covered operation is *also* logged-by-default — the honest definition of "a signature
would actually fire in a stock project."

---

## 3. The chaining layer: capabilities

Per-event signatures never reason about **chains**. To express multi-step attacks purely in
the graph — again, no model — each technique is annotated with the **capabilities** it grants,
and capabilities unlock further techniques (`library/capabilities.py`). All rules are
deterministic and auditable.

- **GRANTS** — e.g. `*.setIamPolicy` on a project → `PROJECT_ADMIN`; `getAccessToken` /
  `serviceAccountKeys.create` → `IMPERSONATE_SA`; `secretmanager.versions.access` →
  `READ_SECRET`.
- **IMPLIES** — capability implications, e.g. `CODE_EXEC_AS_SA ⟹ IMPERSONATE_SA`,
  `CUSTOM_ROLE ⟹ PROJECT_ADMIN`, `ORG_ADMIN ⟹ PROJECT_ADMIN`.
- **UNLOCKS** — `IMPERSONATE_SA` satisfies the `iam.serviceAccounts.actAs` precondition of the
  deploy-as-SA techniques, so `(A)-[:ENABLES]->(B)` is materialised whenever A's capabilities
  unlock B.

Crown jewels: `PROJECT_ADMIN`, `ORG_ADMIN`, `SA_KEY_PERSIST`, `READ_SECRET`, `DECRYPT_KMS`.
The `ENABLES` subgraph lets a query walk "foothold → … → project owner" with no rule reasoning
across any hop — the class of scenario a per-event engine is structurally blind to.

